    "parts": "Chrysophyllum ferrugineum is a species of tree that is native to tropical Africa, and its bark and leaves are used in traditional medicine. The bark is often used to treat various health conditions, including fever, rheumatism, and digestive issues. The leaves, on the other hand, are used to treat respiratory problems, such as coughs and bronchitis. In addition, the plant's roots are also used in traditional medicine, although their specific uses are less well-documented. Further research is needed to fully understand the medicinal properties of Chrysophyllum ferrugineum.",
    "intro": "Chrysophyllum ferrugineum, also known as the rusty ironwood, is a tropical plant species belonging to the family Sapotaceae, native to the Americas and the Caribbean. The plant has been traditionally used in folk medicine, where it is valued for its potential health benefits, including the treatment of fever, cough, and respiratory issues, as well as its antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties. Chrysophyllum ferrugineum contains bioactive constituents such as flavonoids, phenolic acids, and alkaloids, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. In traditional herbal medicine, the plant is often used to make teas, infusions, and extracts, which are used to treat a range of health conditions, including colds, flu, and bronchial infections."
